2026-04-21 02:38:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['All switch indicator LEDs in Control Modules 1-8'] hypothesis_explanation="Given the additional clarification that all the switch indicator (red) LEDs in modules 1-8 are missing, I previously hypothesized this as the fault, but repair action result says those are NOT the issue. Since all switches are ON, all mechanical connections and wiring polarity are fine, and both load lamps do not light, another fault path may be a hidden open circuit in the wiring inside one of the control modules (e.g., a missing jumper/wire where the LED should be, so that without the LED installed, the module internally remains open circuit and current cannot pass). Since all 8 modules report missing indicator LEDs, and these cannot be replaced, and the system works by passing current through the main path, I now suspect that the design relies on the LED being physically present to complete the series main conductor inside each control module, i.e., the absence of the indicator LEDs intentionally leaves the control modules open circuit. Therefore, my revised fault hypothesis is that the circuit design has a dependency such that the indicator LEDs must be installed for current to pass; with all 8 missing, the series chain is open in 8 locations. These are not \x1calling\x1d the LED component as electronically \x1cfaulty\x1d, but as mechanically/fundamentally \x1cmissing (causing open circuit)\x1d. Suspected fault: indicator LEDs (as 'jumpers') missing in all 8 control modules."
